title: Prep roundup: Botcher just misses state trip
text:
Prep roundup: Botcher just misses state trip Daily Tribune Media 10:14 p.m. CDT October 5, 2015 Sport balls CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
TOMAH – At the turn, Wisconsin Rapids junior Cierra Botcher was in second place at Monday’s WIAA Division 1 girls golf sectional. 
Botcher faltered on the back nine, shooting a 46 for an 18-hole total of 85, at Hiawatha Golf Course, missing a trip to state by one strike. 
An eight on the 13th hole was her worst hole of the day. 
Marshfield senior Jordyn Fitzgerald, an individual qualifier, shot a 91 and placed tied for 21st place. 
The Stevens Point Area Senior High girls placed fourth with 367 points. 
Mary McDonald led the Panthers with a score of 85. 
Team scores (Top two teams advance to state): 1. Onalaska 347; 2. Eau Claire Memorial 353; 3. Rice Lake 365; 4. SPASH 367; 5. River Falls 370; 6. Tomah 371; 7. Eau Claire North 375; 8. Sparta 
Individual qualifiers: 1. Lexi Jonas (Hudson), 78; 3. Ilayna Long (Tomah), 81; 4. Alyssa Bee (EC North), 84. 
SPASH: Mary McDonald 85, Abbie Ter Maat 93, Kelsey Shuda 85, Brooke Tuszka 95, Jessica Barber 97. 
GIRLS TENNIS 
SPASH subsectional 
STEVENS POINT – Junior McKenzie Wentland and the doubles team of Mia Iwinski and Ellie Schuerman were the only members of the Raiders to pick up a win as no member of the Wisconsin Rapids team advanced from the Division 1 subsectional. 
Wentland defeated Marshfield’s Hanah Gadke 4-6, 6-0, 6-0 in her first match at No. 2 singles but then fell in straight sets to SPASH’s Sabrina Tang, the top seed. 
Iwinski and Schuerman downed Wausau West’s Kaomi Yang/Sydney Turner 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (4) in an opening-round match at No. 3 doubles. The duo then fell to a Rhinelander team in the next round in straight sets. 
Rapids’ Kairlyn Hess lost her opening matchup at No. 1 singles as did Hannah Wangen and Zoe Gilmaster at No. 3 and No. 4 singles, respectively. 
The Raiders top two doubles teams — Allie Henke/McCartney Sullivan and Mal Herman/Paige Vruwink — both lost their opening-round matches. 
SPASH advanced a player in all four singles brackets and three doubles brackets as well and finished with 24 points to top the eight-team subsectional field. 
Rhinelander finished second with 20 points, and Wausau East and Marshfield tied for third with eight.
